<div type="definition">
<p>MOVE so as to CEASE to BE-IN a PLACE.</p>
    </div>
<div type="notes">
<div type="old-chinese-criteria">
<p>1. The general word for leaving one place for another is qù 去 (ant. liú 留 "remain").</p>
<p>2. Chū 出 (ant. rù 入 "remain inside") refers to the leaving of an enclosed space.</p>
<p>3. Wǎng 往 (ant.* jū 居 "stay at home") focusses not only on the leaving but especially on the direction a person takes after leaving.</p>
<p>4. Lí 離 focusses on the distance established by leaving between a person and the place which he leaves.</p>
        </div>
<div type="modern-chinese-criteria">
<p>離開</p>
<p>撤離</p>
<p>背離</p>
<p>開走</p>
<p>去</p>
<p>走</p>
<p>起開</p>
<p>滾蛋</p>
<p>滾開</p>
<p>滾</p>
<p>奪門而出</p>
<p>揚長而去</p>
<p>別去 (lit/archaic) refers to a person walking away.</p>
        </div>
<div type="old-chinese-contrasts">
<p>LEIBNIZ 6.4 P. 54: A b i r e desinere adesse.</p>
        </div>
    </div>
